description:
Implement the TerminalView widget struct, the avt→ratatui cell mapping, color/attribute conversion, and cursor rendering. This ticket covers rendering when the host terminal is at least as large as the recording (no viewport scrolling needed — that's 2.2.2).

## Tasks

1. Create `crates/speedrun/src/ui.rs` with the TerminalView widget struct:

   ```rust
   use ratatui::buffer::Buffer;
   use ratatui::layout::Rect;
   use ratatui::style::{Color, Modifier};
   use ratatui::widgets::Widget;
   use speedrun_core::CursorState;

   /// Renders an avt terminal cell grid to a ratatui buffer.
   pub struct TerminalView<'a> {
       /// The terminal line grid from `player.screen()`.
       lines: &'a [avt::Line],
       /// Cursor state from `player.cursor()`.
       cursor: CursorState,
       /// Recording dimensions (cols, rows).
       size: (u16, u16),
   }

   impl<'a> TerminalView<'a> {
       pub fn new(lines: &'a [avt::Line], cursor: CursorState, size: (u16, u16)) -> Self {
           Self { lines, cursor, size }
       }
   }
   ```

2. Implement the color mapping function:

   ```rust
   /// Map an avt color to a ratatui color.
   fn map_color(color: Option<avt::Color>) -> Color {
       match color {
           None => Color::Reset,
           Some(avt::Color::Indexed(i)) => Color::Indexed(i),
           Some(avt::Color::RGB(rgb)) => Color::Rgb(rgb.r, rgb.g, rgb.b),
       }
   }
   ```

3. Implement the attribute mapping function:

   ```rust
   /// Map avt Pen attributes to ratatui Modifier flags.
   fn map_modifiers(pen: &avt::Pen) -> Modifier {
       let mut mods = Modifier::empty();
       if pen.is_bold() { mods |= Modifier::BOLD; }
       if pen.is_faint() { mods |= Modifier::DIM; }
       if pen.is_italic() { mods |= Modifier::ITALIC; }
       if pen.is_underline() { mods |= Modifier::UNDERLINED; }
       if pen.is_strikethrough() { mods |= Modifier::CROSSED_OUT; }
       if pen.is_blink() { mods |= Modifier::SLOW_BLINK; }
       if pen.is_inverse() { mods |= Modifier::REVERSED; }
       mods
   }
   ```

4. Implement the `Widget` trait:

   ```rust
   impl Widget for TerminalView<'_> {
       fn render(self, area: Rect, buf: &mut Buffer) {
           if area.width == 0 || area.height == 0 {
               return;
           }

           let render_rows = (self.size.1 as u16).min(area.height);
           let render_cols = (self.size.0 as u16).min(area.width);

           for row in 0..render_rows {
               let line_idx = row as usize;
               if line_idx >= self.lines.len() {
                   break;
               }

               let line = &self.lines[line_idx];
               let mut col: u16 = 0;

               for (ch, pen) in line.cells() {
                   if col >= render_cols {
                       break;
                   }

                   let cell = buf.get_mut(area.x + col, area.y + row);

                   // Set character
                   cell.set_char(ch);

                   // Set colors
                   cell.set_fg(map_color(pen.foreground()));
                   cell.set_bg(map_color(pen.background()));

                   // Set attributes — direct assignment for full overwrite
                   cell.modifier = map_modifiers(&pen);

                   // Handle wide characters: check char width
                   let char_width = unicode_width::UnicodeWidthChar::width(ch).unwrap_or(1);
                   if char_width == 2 && col + 1 < render_cols {
                       // Wide char: skip next cell (ratatui handles this
                       // if we set the symbol properly, but we need to
                       // advance our column counter past the second cell)
                       col += 2;
                   } else {
                       col += 1;
                   }
               }
           }

           // Render cursor
           if self.cursor.visible {
               let cx = self.cursor.col as u16;
               let cy = self.cursor.row as u16;
               if cx < render_cols && cy < render_rows {
                   let cell = buf.get_mut(area.x + cx, area.y + cy);
                   cell.modifier |= Modifier::REVERSED;
               }
           }
       }
   }
   ```

   **Important note on wide characters**: The `line.cells()` iterator yields one `(char, Pen)` per cell column. For a wide character like '👩' (width 2), avt stores the wide char in the first cell and a placeholder (typically a space or zero-width) in the second cell. The iterator yields both. We need to handle this by detecting wide chars and using `set_symbol()` instead of `set_char()` for the first cell, then calling `set_skip(true)` on the second cell. Test with actual data to verify avt's behavior.

   **Alternative approach if `cells()` yields per-column**: If avt's `cells()` iterator already accounts for wide chars by yielding one entry per column slot, then simply iterating and setting `set_char(ch)` on each cell works. The wide char's second column would be a space/placeholder. Verify with `alternate_buffer.cast` or test data.

5. Add `mod ui;` to `main.rs`.

6. Add `unicode-width` dependency to `crates/speedrun/Cargo.toml` (needed for char width detection). Note: this may already be a transitive dependency via avt or ratatui — check before adding.

## Acceptance criteria

- [ ] `TerminalView` struct is constructible from `&[avt::Line]`, `CursorState`, and `(u16, u16)` size
- [ ] `Widget` trait is implemented — `render()` writes cells to the ratatui buffer
- [ ] `map_color()` correctly maps: `None` → `Color::Reset`, `Indexed(u8)` → `Color::Indexed(u8)`, `RGB(RGB8)` → `Color::Rgb(r, g, b)`
- [ ] `map_modifiers()` correctly maps all 7 avt attributes to ratatui Modifier flags
- [ ] Cursor is rendered with `REVERSED` modifier at the correct position when visible
- [ ] Cursor is not rendered when `cursor.visible == false`
- [ ] Zero-size area doesn't panic (early return)
- [ ] When recording is smaller than area, content renders at top-left (extra space unused)
- [ ] When recording is larger than area, content is clipped (no panic)
- [ ] `cargo build -p speedrun` compiles cleanly
- [ ] `cargo clippy --workspace -- -D warnings` passes
- [ ] `cargo fmt --check` passes

NOTES:

### avt Cell iteration detail

The `avt::Line::cells()` method returns `impl Iterator<Item = (char, Pen)>`. Each cell in the line is yielded — for an 80-column terminal, a line has 80 cells. Wide characters (e.g., CJK, emoji) occupy 2 cell slots. In avt's internal representation (`Vec<Cell>`), a wide char is stored in one cell but occupies the visual width of two columns. The iterator yields every cell in the `Vec<Cell>`, so for a wide character followed by normal text, the sequence is:

```
('👩', pen)   ← wide char (char_width = 2)
(' ', pen)    ← filler/placeholder for second column (if avt uses this pattern)
('a', pen)    ← normal char
```

However, avt may use a different internal convention. The safest approach is to iterate with column tracking using `unicode_width` to determine how many columns each character occupies. If `cells()` yields a filler character (like a null or space) for the second half of a wide char, simply write it to the buffer — ratatui will handle it correctly as long as the first cell's symbol is set properly.

**Practical approach**: Start with the simple per-cell mapping. If wide chars render incorrectly, switch to using `line.segments()` which groups consecutive cells with the same pen, giving `Segment { text, pen, offset, char_width }`. The `offset` field gives the column position and `char_width` indicates whether chars are single or double width.

### Pen field access

`avt::Pen` fields (`foreground`, `background`, `intensity`, `attrs`) are `pub(crate)` — not directly accessible from outside avt. Use the public accessor methods:
- `pen.foreground() -> Option<Color>` (not `pen.foreground`)
- `pen.background() -> Option<Color>` (not `pen.background`)
- `pen.is_bold()`, etc.

### Verification commands

```bash
cargo build -p speedrun
cargo clippy --workspace -- -D warnings
cargo fmt --check
```

notes:
## Critical: dependency setup

The `speedrun` crate does NOT currently have `avt` or `rgb` as direct dependencies. The TerminalView widget needs to reference `avt::Line`, `avt::Pen`, `avt::Color`, and `rgb::RGB8` types. These must be added to `crates/speedrun/Cargo.toml`:

```toml
[dependencies]
speedrun-core = { path = "../speedrun-core" }
ratatui.workspace = true
crossterm.workspace = true
clap.workspace = true
avt.workspace = true
rgb.workspace = true
```

If ticket 2.1.1 has already added these (see its notes), they'll already be there. If not, add them in this ticket.

## `unicode-width` is NOT needed

After reviewing avt's internals: `avt::Line` stores one `Cell` per column position (not per character). For an 80-column terminal, `line.cells()` always yields exactly 80 `(char, Pen)` items. Wide characters are stored in the first cell, and avt puts a space/placeholder in the subsequent cell. This means a simple 1:1 cell mapping works WITHOUT explicitly tracking character widths.

The simplest correct approach: iterate `line.cells()` and write each `(char, Pen)` to the corresponding ratatui buffer cell at position `col`. Increment col by 1 for every cell. Do NOT add `unicode-width` as a dependency.

If a wide character is encountered, `set_char(ch)` will write the wide char to the ratatui cell. Ratatui internally handles the display width. The next cell from avt will be a space/placeholder that gets written to the next ratatui cell, which ratatui's diffing will handle correctly.

**Simplified render loop**:
```rust
for row in 0..render_rows {
    if (row as usize) >= self.lines.len() { break; }
    let line = &self.lines[row as usize];

    for (col, (ch, pen)) in line.cells().enumerate() {
        if col as u16 >= render_cols { break; }
        let cell = buf.get_mut(area.x + col as u16, area.y + row);
        cell.set_char(ch);
        cell.set_fg(map_color(pen.foreground()));
        cell.set_bg(map_color(pen.background()));
        cell.modifier = map_modifiers(&pen);
    }
}
```

## `mod ui;` addition

Add `mod ui;` to `main.rs`. If Epic 2.1's tickets haven't been completed yet (since the epics run in parallel), the agent should add `mod ui;` to the existing `main.rs` stub. Since the file only has 3 lines, this is safe. However, `mod ui;` alone without using it will trigger a dead code warning. Use `#[allow(dead_code)]` on the module declaration or add `pub` to make clippy happy:

```rust
mod ui;
```

Since `ui.rs` types aren't used from `main.rs` yet, suppress warnings with either:
- `#[allow(clippy::all)] mod ui;` — too broad
- Just make all public items in ui.rs `pub` and add `pub mod ui;` in main.rs
- Or accept that integration happens later and gate it

The cleanest approach: use `pub mod ui;` and make TerminalView and friends `pub`. They'll be used when Epic 2.3 wires everything together.

## Pen accessor: by value, not reference

`line.cells()` returns `(char, Pen)` where `Pen: Copy`. The `pen` variable is owned (by value). Calling `pen.foreground()` works via auto-ref. In `map_modifiers`, pass `&pen` since the function takes `&avt::Pen`.

description:
Add viewport scrolling to TerminalView for when the host terminal is smaller than the recording dimensions. The viewport follows the cursor position so the user always sees the active area.

## Tasks

1. Define `ViewportState` to track scroll offsets:

   ```rust
   /// Tracks the visible portion of the recording when the host terminal
   /// is smaller than the recording dimensions.
   #[derive(Debug, Default, Clone)]
   pub struct ViewportState {
       /// Horizontal scroll offset (column of the recording at the left edge).
       pub scroll_x: u16,
       /// Vertical scroll offset (row of the recording at the top edge).
       pub scroll_y: u16,
   }
   ```

2. Add a method to compute the scroll offsets based on cursor position:

   ```rust
   impl ViewportState {
       /// Update scroll offsets to keep the cursor visible within the viewport.
       ///
       /// The cursor should stay within the visible area, with a small margin
       /// when possible. If the recording fits entirely within the viewport
       /// (in either dimension), the offset for that dimension stays at 0.
       pub fn follow_cursor(
           &mut self,
           cursor_col: u16,
           cursor_row: u16,
           recording_cols: u16,
           recording_rows: u16,
           viewport_width: u16,
           viewport_height: u16,
       ) {
           // Horizontal: no scrolling needed if recording fits
           if recording_cols <= viewport_width {
               self.scroll_x = 0;
           } else {
               // Keep cursor visible — if cursor is outside current viewport, adjust
               let margin = 2u16.min(viewport_width / 4); // small margin, at least 2 cols
               if cursor_col < self.scroll_x + margin {
                   self.scroll_x = cursor_col.saturating_sub(margin);
               } else if cursor_col >= self.scroll_x + viewport_width - margin {
                   self.scroll_x = (cursor_col + margin + 1).saturating_sub(viewport_width);
               }
               // Clamp: don't scroll past the end of the recording
               let max_scroll = recording_cols.saturating_sub(viewport_width);
               self.scroll_x = self.scroll_x.min(max_scroll);
           }

           // Vertical: same logic
           if recording_rows <= viewport_height {
               self.scroll_y = 0;
           } else {
               let margin = 1u16.min(viewport_height / 4);
               if cursor_row < self.scroll_y + margin {
                   self.scroll_y = cursor_row.saturating_sub(margin);
               } else if cursor_row >= self.scroll_y + viewport_height - margin {
                   self.scroll_y = (cursor_row + margin + 1).saturating_sub(viewport_height);
               }
               let max_scroll = recording_rows.saturating_sub(viewport_height);
               self.scroll_y = self.scroll_y.min(max_scroll);
           }
       }
   }
   ```

3. Update `TerminalView` to accept scroll offsets:

   ```rust
   pub struct TerminalView<'a> {
       lines: &'a [avt::Line],
       cursor: CursorState,
       size: (u16, u16),
       scroll_x: u16,
       scroll_y: u16,
   }

   impl<'a> TerminalView<'a> {
       pub fn new(lines: &'a [avt::Line], cursor: CursorState, size: (u16, u16)) -> Self {
           Self { lines, cursor, size, scroll_x: 0, scroll_y: 0 }
       }

       pub fn with_scroll(mut self, scroll_x: u16, scroll_y: u16) -> Self {
           self.scroll_x = scroll_x;
           self.scroll_y = scroll_y;
           self
       }
   }
   ```

4. Update the `Widget::render()` implementation to account for scroll offsets:

   ```rust
   impl Widget for TerminalView<'_> {
       fn render(self, area: Rect, buf: &mut Buffer) {
           if area.width == 0 || area.height == 0 {
               return;
           }

           let render_rows = (self.size.1).min(area.height);
           let render_cols = (self.size.0).min(area.width);

           for row in 0..render_rows {
               let line_idx = (row + self.scroll_y) as usize;
               if line_idx >= self.lines.len() {
                   break;
               }

               let line = &self.lines[line_idx];
               let mut src_col: u16 = 0;
               let mut dst_col: u16 = 0;

               for (ch, pen) in line.cells() {
                   // Skip cells before the scroll offset
                   if src_col < self.scroll_x {
                       let char_width = unicode_width::UnicodeWidthChar::width(ch).unwrap_or(1) as u16;
                       src_col += char_width;
                       continue;
                   }

                   if dst_col >= render_cols {
                       break;
                   }

                   let cell = buf.get_mut(area.x + dst_col, area.y + row);
                   cell.set_char(ch);
                   cell.set_fg(map_color(pen.foreground()));
                   cell.set_bg(map_color(pen.background()));
                   cell.modifier = map_modifiers(&pen);

                   let char_width = unicode_width::UnicodeWidthChar::width(ch).unwrap_or(1) as u16;
                   src_col += char_width;
                   dst_col += char_width.min(render_cols - dst_col);
               }
           }

           // Render cursor (adjusted for scroll offset)
           if self.cursor.visible {
               let cx = (self.cursor.col as u16).checked_sub(self.scroll_x);
               let cy = (self.cursor.row as u16).checked_sub(self.scroll_y);
               if let (Some(cx), Some(cy)) = (cx, cy) {
                   if cx < render_cols && cy < render_rows {
                       let cell = buf.get_mut(area.x + cx, area.y + cy);
                       cell.modifier |= Modifier::REVERSED;
                   }
               }
           }
       }
   }
   ```

5. Add `ViewportState` to `App` struct (in `app.rs`):

   ```rust
   pub struct App {
       pub player: Player,
       pub show_controls: bool,
       pub last_interaction: Instant,
       pub should_quit: bool,
       pub viewport: ui::ViewportState,
   }
   ```

   Update `App::render()` to use viewport:
   ```rust
   fn render(&mut self, frame: &mut Frame) {
       let area = frame.area();
       let (cols, rows) = self.player.size();
       let cursor = self.player.cursor();

       self.viewport.follow_cursor(
           cursor.col as u16,
           cursor.row as u16,
           cols, rows,
           area.width, area.height,
       );

       let view = ui::TerminalView::new(self.player.screen(), cursor, (cols, rows))
           .with_scroll(self.viewport.scroll_x, self.viewport.scroll_y);

       frame.render_widget(view, area);
   }
   ```

